04867nam a22007215i 9781512807899DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20161999pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)980246135  a97815128078997 a10.9783/97815128078992doi  a(DE-B1597)475743  a(OCoLC)979911613  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHV1553 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a362.4/0973/090342211 aKlages, Mary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWoeful Afflictions :bDisability and Sentimentality in Victorian America /cMary Klages.  aReprint 2016 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (250 p.) :b10 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction: Disability and Sentimentality -- t1. The Semiotics of Disability -- t2. Institutional Meanings for Blind Bodies -- t3. Sentimental Posters -- t4. The Angel in the Text -- t5. Institutional Sentimentalism -- t6. Laura Bridgman -- t7. Can the Blind Girl Speak? -- t8. Helen Keller -- t9. Redefining Disability and Sentimentality: The Miracle Worker -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom Tiny Tim to Helen Keller, disabled people in the nineteenth century were portrayed in sentimental terms, as afflicted beings whose sufferings afforded ablebodied people opportunities to practice empathy and compassion. In all kinds of representations of disability, from popular fiction to the reports of institutions established for the education and rehabilitation of disabled people, the equation of disability and sentimentality served a variety of social functions, from ensuring the continued existence of a sympathetic sensibility in a hard-hearted, market-driven world, to asserting the selfhood and equality of disabled adults. Unique in its focus on blindness and its examination of the interplay between institutional discourse and popular literature, Woeful Afflictions offers a detailed historical analysis of the types of cultural work performed by sentimental representations of disability in public reports and lectures, exhibitions, novels, stories, poems, autobiographical writings, and popular media portrayals from the 1830s through the 1890s in the United States. Woeful Afflictions combines contemporary scholarship on sentimentalism with the most recent works on the cultural meanings of disability to argue that sentimentalism, with its emphasis on creating emotional identifications between texts and readers, both reinforces existing associations between disability and otherness and works to rewrite those associations in portraying disabled people, in their emotional capacities, as no different from the ablebodied. This book will interest anyone concerned with disability studies and the social construction of the body, with the history of education and of public institutional care in the United States, and with autobiographical writings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aPeople with disabilities in literature. 0aPeople with disabilities in mass mediaxHistory. 0aPeople with disabilitieszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z97831104425260 cprintz978081223499240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978151280789940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512807899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781512807899.jpg  a978-3-11-044252-6  Penn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  a